Projet 6 - Classification Automatique des Biens de Consommation¶

Partie 1 de 3¶

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Le Contexte¶

Lentreprise "Place de march", qui souhaite lancer une marketplace e-commerce, voudrait mettre en place un moteur de classification: la catgorie d'un article est attribue automatiquement aprs le tlchargement d'une photo de l'article. L'entreprise attend que un tel moteur de classification a les bnfices suivantes :

  • augmenter la fiabilit de la classification
  • une facilit d'utilisation
    • pour les vendeurs (qui entrent pour l'instant entrent cette info manuellement)
    • pour les achteurs pour leur recherche de produit

1.2 Objectif¶

  • Etudier la faisabilit d'un moteur de classification
    • analyse de jeu de donnes
    • prtraitement des dscriptions (texte) et des images
    • rduction de dimension
    • clustering

1.3 Résumé de ce Notebook¶

Dans ce notebook, on traite le texte de la description du produit en utilisant des librairies NLTK et SpaCy. Le texte est converti en tokens et lemmatis. Une prmire analyse sur les tokens (les mots dans le texte) et les catgories de produit est faite. Finalement, la description tokenise et lemmatise est exporte pour le clustering et une analyse plus pousse.

Conclusions:

  • Le jeu de donnes est complte et quilibr entre les catgories.
  • Il y a environ 4600-4800 tokens uniques dont la grande majorit est trs infrquent dans le corpus.
  • Il y a des tokens qui sont trs frquents et se trouvent dans tous les document -> des stopwords spcifique au corpus
  • La lemmatisation n'est pas parfaite - certains mots ne sont pas dans les dictionnaires respectives.

def decompose_category_tree_to_levels(category_tree, n_levels=1, split_str=' >> ', strip_str='"[]', fillin=False):
    '''Function that decomposes a string representing a category_tree into different levels. \\
    The strings to be stripped off of this string and the strings used to delimit the levels can be entered into \\
    this function : strip_str and split_str
    The output result is a dataframe containing the columns: \\
    the category_tree as a list, the depth of the tree, the levels (upto n_levels or the maximum tree depth).
    The missing category levels further down the tree are filled in with the variable fillin'''
    level_df = pd.DataFrame()
    level_df['category_list'] = category_tree.str.strip(strip_str).str.split(split_str)
    level_df['category_tree_depth'] = level_df['category_list'].apply(len)
    n_levels_max = level_df['category_tree_depth'].max()
    if n_levels_max < n_levels : n_levels = n_levels_max
    if fillin:
        level_df['category_list'] = [fillin_list(ls, n_levels) for ls in level_df['category_list']]
    for n in range(n_levels):
        level_df['category_level'+str(n+1)] = [cat[n] if (n<len(cat)) else np.nan for cat in level_df['category_list']]
    return level_df
In [7]:
def fillin_list(ls, ls_length, fillin=None):
    '''Helper function to extend a list 'ls' to length 'ls_length' with the value 'fillin'. '''
    if fillin == None:
        fillin = ls[-1] if len(ls) else np.nan
    return ls + (ls_length - len(ls))*[fillin]

def tagmap(x):
    '''Returns a default dictionary converting the pos_tag from nltk to wordnet POS tags. '''
    tag_map = defaultdict(lambda : wn.NOUN)
    tag_map['J'] = wn.ADJ
    tag_map['V'] = wn.VERB
    tag_map['R'] = wn.ADV
    x=x[0]
    return tag_map[x]
In [9]:
def tokenize_and_lemmatize_with_nltk(txt_srs, stopwords=[]):
    '''Tokenize and Lemmatize a text using NLTK together with wordnet.'''
    tokenizer = WordPunctTokenizer()
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    txt_df = pd.DataFrame()
    txt_df['tokens_with_pos'] = [txt for txt in txt_srs.apply(lambda x: tokenizer.tokenize(x)).apply(pos_tag)]
    txt_df['lemmas'] = txt_df['tokens_with_pos'].apply(
        lambda x : [lemmatizer.lemmatize(token, tagmap(tag)).lower() for token, tag in x 
                    if not ((token.lower() in stopwords) | (lemmatizer.lemmatize(token, tagmap(tag)).lower() in stopwords))])
    txt_df['document'] = txt_df['lemmas'].apply(lambda x : ' '.join(x))
    return txt_df

def tokenize_and_lemmatize_with_spacy(txt_srs, stopwords=[]):
    '''Tokenize and Lemmatize a text using Spacy.'''
    txt_df = pd.DataFrame()
    txt_df['tokens'] = [list(txt) for txt in txt_srs.apply(lambda x: nlp(x))]
    txt_df['lemmas'] = txt_df['tokens'].apply(lambda x : [str(token.lemma_).lower() for token in x 
                                                          if not (token.is_space | token.is_punct | token.is_stop | 
                                                          (str(token.lemma_).lower() in stopwords))])
    txt_df['document'] = txt_df['lemmas'].apply(lambda x : ' '.join(x))
    return txt_df

def replace_chars_with_space(txt, char_list=[]):
    '''Replace the Characters in char_list with a space.'''
    for char in char_list:
        txt = txt.replace(char, ' ')    
    return txt

def token_counter(doc_srs):
    '''Create a Counter object, which counts the occurences of the tokens in a corpus.'''
    all_tokens = ' '.join(doc_srs).split()
    return Counter(all_tokens)
In [13]:
def drop_stopwords(doc_srs, stopwords = []):
    '''Function to drop user defined stopwords from a corpus.'''
    doc_df = pd.DataFrame()
    doc_df['document_reduced'] = [[t for t in doc.split() if t not in stopwords] for doc in doc_srs]
    doc_df['document_reduced'] = doc_df['document_reduced'].apply(' '.join)
    return doc_df
In [14]:
def unfrequent_tokens(doc_srs, mincount=1):
    '''Function that finds and returns the tokens that occur less than 'mincoutn'-times in the text. '''
    stopwords =[]
    for t in token_counter(doc_srs).most_common()[::-1]:
        if t[1] < mincount :
            stopwords.append(t[0])
        else:
            break
    return stopwords
In [15]:
def drop_unfrequent_tokens(doc_srs, mincount=1):
    '''Function that drops tokens with an occurence of less than 'mincount' from the corpus. '''
    stopwords = unfrequent_tokens(doc_srs, mincount)
    doc_df = drop_stopwords(doc_srs, stopwords)
    return doc_df

def create_observation_matrix(text_df, doc, cat):
    '''Function that counts the occurences of the tokens in a corpus as a function of the document categorie 'cat'. '''
    counter_df = text_df.groupby(by=cat)[doc].apply(
                     ' '.join).apply(lambda x : pd.Series(Counter(x.split()))).fillna(0)
    counter_df = counter_df.join(counter_df.sum(axis=1).rename('TOTAL'))
    counter_df = counter_df.append(counter_df.sum(axis=0).rename('TOTAL'))
    return counter_df
In [17]:
def create_expected_observation_matrix(counter_df):
    '''Function that returns the expected token counts per category from an observation matrix if there was no difference
    between the different categories.'''
    name='TOTAL'
    tx = pd.DataFrame(counter_df.iloc[:,-1].rename(name))
    ty = pd.DataFrame(counter_df.iloc[-1,:].rename(name))
    n = counter_df.iloc[-1,-1]
    indep_df = tx.dot(ty.T) / n
    return indep_df
In [18]:
def create_chisquared_measure_matrix(counter_df, indep_df):
    '''Function that returns a Chi_Squared matrix given an observation and en expected observation of occurences.'''
    measure_df = (counter_df-indep_df)**2/indep_df
    measure_df.iloc[-1,:] = measure_df.sum(axis=0)
    measure_df.iloc[:,-1] = measure_df.sum(axis=1)
    return measure_df
In [19]:
def create_documentfrequency_matrix(text_df, doc, cat):
    '''Function that returns the document frequency of a token as a count.'''
    docfreq_df = text_df[doc].apply(lambda x : pd.Series(Counter(set(x.split())))).fillna(0)
    docfreq_df[cat] = text_df[cat]
    docfreq_df = docfreq_df.groupby(by=cat).sum()
    docfreq_df = docfreq_df.join(docfreq_df.sum(axis=1).rename('TOTAL'))
    docfreq_df = docfreq_df.append(docfreq_df.sum(axis=0).rename('TOTAL'))
    return docfreq_df

cat = 'category_level1'

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,4, figsize = (14,6))
for i, cl in enumerate(text_df[cat].unique()):
    # Apply the wordcloud to the text.
    select = (text_df[cat] == cl)
    wordcloud.generate(' '.join(text_df['description'][select].str.lower()))
    # add interpolation = bilinear to smooth things out
    #print(i%2, i//2)
    ax = axes[i//4][i%4]
    ax.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    # and remove the axis
    ax.set_title(cl)
    ax.axis("off")
